{"id": 223771580, "title": "California mom fined $88K after kids collect clams from shore", "text": "\u201cIt made me really sad and depressed, and it kind of ruined our trip,\u201d said Russ. The Department of Fish and Wildlife\u2019s Lt. Matthew Gil said the rules are in place to protect the species of shellfish. \u201cThe reason we have these regulations is because we have to let them get to 4 1/2 inches so they can spawn, so they can have offspring every year, and they have juvenile clams,\u201d said Gil. It\u2019s important to educate yourself and your children before going ashore, Gil added. \u201cIf you have a dead sand dollar, a dead animal, or something like that, or you have a broken seashell, that\u2019s fine,\u201d Gil said. \u201cPismo clams \u2014 what you\u2019re going to see is both shells will be intact together.\u201d If you can\u2019t take them a part very easily, it\u2019s a clam.", "summary": "She might have been better off selling seashells by the seashore. Alas, that wasn\u2019t the case, and a California mom was hit with a major fine following what can accurately be described as a bizarre ordeal. Charlotte Russ and her family took a trip to Pismo, Calif., at the end of last year, and the [&#8230;]", "url": "https://torontosun.com/news/world/california-mom-fined-88k-after-kids-collect-clams-from-shore", "image": "https://smartcdn.gprod.postmedia.digital/torontosun/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/GettyImages-1098321614.jpg?quality=100&strip=all", "video": "https://cdn.jwplayer.com/videos/RwshZLr2-SZnIQkEn.mp4", "publish_date": "2024-05-26 16:55:35", "author": "Postmedia News", "authors": ["Postmedia News"], "language": "en", "source_country": "CA", "sentiment": -0.212}